Revision history for App-PerlGraph

0.065     2026-06-26
          - Fix (found by battle-testing pcg on a real 643-file Moose/Mojo app): `pcg checkcalls` produced
            ~755 findings on it, ~91% FALSE POSITIVES. Two systematic causes, both now fixed -- the count
            dropped to 65:
            * ROLES. A role's `$self` is the (unknown) CONSUMING class, so a `$self->consumer_method` call
              inside a role is unverifiable -- but checkcalls was treating the role itself as the receiver
              class and flagging every such call (596 of the 755). The extractor now FLAGS role packages
              (`metadata.role`) -- recognizing `use Mojo::Base -role`, `use Moo::Role` / `Moose::Role` /
              `Mouse::Role`, `use Role::Tiny`, and the native/Object::Pad `role NAME {...}` -- and checkcalls
              skips a receiver that is a role. EXTRACTION_VERSION 8 -> 9 (re-index picks it up).
            * CPAN DEPS. A `pcg index --deps`-indexed dependency has an INCOMPLETE API (its XS methods aren't
              in the .pm), so checkcalls reporting "class Foo defines no `add`" for a vendored XS class
              (Algorithm::BloomFilter, Mojo::UserAgent, Sereal::Encoder, ...) is wrong. checkcalls now treats
              a `metadata.cpan`-flagged class as external (excluded from the closed-MRO test), like any other
              uncovered external class.
          - Fix (same battle-test): three `pcg checkargs` false-positive sources. (1) a `qw/a b c/` argument was
            counted as ONE arg instead of its WORD COUNT, so a correct call like `$self->m(qw/x y/)` could be
            reported as too-few-args -- it now counts the words. (2) a hash/array SLICE argument (`@h{...}` /
            `@a[...]`) has an indeterminate element count but was counted as one arg (so `$self->m($a, @h{qw/x y z/})`
            looked like 2 args, not 4) -- a slice now makes the call indeterminate and skipped, like a splat.
            (3) a `$obj->method` site was matched to a same-named method in the CALLER's own package even when the
            invocant was NOT `$self`/`$class` (e.g. `$block->provider` wrongly matched a 3-arg `Campaign::provider`)
            -- the same-package match is now restricted to `$self`/`$class` receivers (the intra-class case it is meant for).
          - Tests +8 (1535 total): t/88 gains role-skip (Mojo::Base -role + Moo::Role, with the role flag
            asserted at extraction) and cpan-exclusion (a cpan-flagged class's missing method is not flagged);
            t/94 gains the qw// word-count and the non-$self-receiver cases. Genuine bugs are still reported and
            the existing no-false-positive guarantees hold.

0.064     2026-06-25
          - New: `pcg taint` / pcg_taint (52 MCP tools) -- SOURCE -> SINK taint paths, the security flagship of
            the 8th wave and a sharper pcg_sinks. It traces a call path from a user-input SOURCE to an injectable
            SINK: the sources are broader than pcg_sinks' routes -- a web endpoint OR any sub that calls a request
            accessor (param / cookie / upload / headers / query_parameters / body_parameters) -- and only DYNAMIC
            sinks (whose command/SQL string is built from a variable, i.e. the injectable ones) are targets, with
            the actual call PATH shown (source -> ... -> sink). A `[local]` hit (source and sink in the SAME sub)
            is ranked first as the highest-confidence. IMPORTANT: this is call-graph REACHABILITY, not value-flow
            -- it proves user input can REACH the sink's sub, not that the specific tainted value lands in the
            sink's argument, so each path is a lead to VERIFY, not a confirmed vulnerability (and $ENV / @ARGV /
            STDIN sources are not yet detected). New Query::taint (dynamic-sink edges + source classification +
            forward BFS over the call graph); Format::taint; CLI `pcg taint`. Closes the 8th wave (deeper
            analysis & action: tidy, smells, pr, change-signature, taint).
          - Fixes (found by the pre-release review loop dogfooding `change-signature` -- it must never write
            non-compiling Perl): three ways it could produce an invalid sub now REFUSE instead.
            (1) `--remove` of a parameter still referenced in the BODY (`sub f () { $x }` after dropping `$x`) --
            the check spans every sigil + the braced `${x}` interpolation form. (2) `--remove` of a parameter
            still referenced in a SURVIVING parameter's DEFAULT (`sub f ($x, $y = $x + 1)` after dropping `$x`).
            (3) any edit whose resulting signature violates Perl's parameter ordering -- a required parameter
            after an optional one (`($a, $b = 5, $c)`), or anything after a slurpy (a `@rest`/`%opts` must be
            last). Each refusal explains how to proceed (remove the uses, rename, give a default, or reorder),
            consistent with the other write tools' refuse-when-unsafe stance. t/103 gains a `perl -c` regression
            guard on the applied result and refusal tests for all five cases.
          - Tests +44 (1528 total): t/104 (+17: a cross-sub path handler -> run_cmd to a dynamic system() sink,
            a local same-sub hit ranked first, a constant-arg system('ls','-l') correctly excluded, the source
            classified a request accessor, the renderer's path arrows + [local] marker + caveat + both empty
            states). t/15 + t/46 assert 52 advertised tools; t/15's doc-sync guard (+2) confirms pcg_taint.
            +25 from the pre-release review hardening: t/15 tools/call dispatch smokes for the five new tools;
            t/102's broken-call + wide-blast render + the affected-tests line; t/103's --at mid-insert, the
            applied-plan render, the remove-used-param refusal + perl -c guard, and the no-signature / malformed-
            add / out-of-range-position / error-render guards; t/104's two Query-level early returns.

0.063     2026-06-25
          - New: `pcg change-signature` / pcg_change_signature (51 MCP tools) -- the SIXTH write tool: change a
            plain function's PARAMETER LIST and propagate it to every resolved call site, the actionable fix for
            a parameter change pcg_checkargs would otherwise flag everywhere. Two conservative operations: ADD a
            parameter (--add '$p' or '$n = 0', at 1-based --at N or appended, inserting --value EXPR (default
            `undef`) at each call site) or REMOVE one (--remove N, dropping that positional argument at each
            site). Function-only: a method ($self/$class first param) is refused, and a $obj->method call site is
            reported to the frontier, because the invocant offsets the positions and the dispatch can't be
            statically tied. A call site whose argument list is statically indeterminate (a splat / deref /
            call-result among the args) or that doesn't reach the touched position is reported for manual review,
            never edited. The definition's signature and every call site are byte-span edits; dry-run unless
            --apply / apply:true. New Refactor::change_signature (+ _rewrite_args / _arg_count / _split_top_commas,
            reusing the inline codemod's call-site machinery); Format::change_signature; CLI `pcg change-signature`;
            wired into the MCP write-tool dispatch beside dedupe/rm.
          - Tests +26 (1484 total): t/103 (+24: add appends to the signature + inserts the value at each
            determinate call site (the splat call and the $obj->method call going to the frontier); remove drops
            the parameter from the definition, every plain call site, and the recursive self-call, leaving the
            indeterminate + method sites untouched; a method is refused; out-of-range position / unknown function
            / missing or conflicting operation are rejected; the renderer). t/15 + t/46 assert 51 advertised
            tools and "six write tools"; t/15's doc-sync guard (+2) confirms pcg_change_signature is surfaced.

0.062     2026-06-25
          - New: `pcg pr <ref>` / pcg_pr (50 MCP tools) -- a SCORED PR-HEALTH GATE for CI, built on top of
            pcg_review: the same change analysis folded into a single 0-100 health score and a PASS / REVIEW /
            BLOCK verdict, so a branch gets one yes/no-ish signal instead of a report to read. Adds what review
            doesn't: it LINTS THE CHANGED FILES for call bugs -- pcg_checkcalls + pcg_checkargs scoped to the
            touched files (broken $obj->method calls and wrong-arity calls in code the PR edits). Score = 100
            minus weighted concerns: 15 per breaking public-API change, 12 per broken call, 10 per wrong-arity
            call, 6 per untested public change, 4 per wide-blast-radius change (>=85 PASS, 60-84 REVIEW, <60
            BLOCK); concerns listed worst-first, with the affected tests to run. A heuristic signal, not a
            substitute for human review. New Review::pr (reuses review() + the changed-file lint + scoring);
            Format::pr; CLI `pcg pr`; wired into the MCP git-block beside review/diff/semver/changelog.
          - Tests +17 (1458 total): t/102 (+15: a fixture removing a public sub (breaking), adding an untested
            public sub, and adding a wrong-arity call in a changed file -> score 100-15-10-6 = 69 = REVIEW; the
            arity finding is scoped to the changed file; the renderer's per-concern sections + scoring legend;
            a clean no-change PR renders PASS 100). t/15 + t/46 assert 50 advertised tools; doc-sync guard (+2).

0.061     2026-06-25
          - New: `pcg smells` / pcg_smells (49 MCP tools) -- structural REFACTORING SMELLS, the named,
            actionable cousins of pcg_hotspots (which only ranks fan-in/out/complexity). Three classic ones,
            all from the call graph: FEATURE ENVY (a method making >= 4 calls into a SINGLE other class and
            none into its own -- it lives in the wrong place; refactor: move it there), GOD CLASS (a class
            with >= 20 methods AND >= 15 distinct external callers -- doing too much; refactor: split it), and
            LONG PARAMETER LIST (a sub whose signature declares >= 5 params, a $self/$class invocant aside;
            refactor: introduce a parameter object). Each smell names its refactoring. Heuristic: feature-envy
            counts only RESOLVED call edges (opaque $obj->method layering doesn't trigger it, though a
            deliberate facade still can) and long-param is signature-based (old-style my(...)=@_ subs invisible).
            `package main` (the shared script/test namespace) and indexed CPAN deps are excluded -- they are
            not classes you'd refactor, and `main` would otherwise aggregate every .t's subs into one bogus
            bucket. New Query::smells (single pass over call edges -> feature-envy + god-class + long-param);
            Format::smells; CLI `pcg smells`; thresholds tunable via opts (fe_min / gc_methods / gc_fanin / lp_min).
          - Tests +18 (1441 total): t/101 (+16: feature-envy names the envied class and ignores a below-
            threshold caller; god-class reports method + external-caller counts and skips a low-fan-in class;
            long-param drops the invocant; the renderer's three sections + clean-state). t/15 + t/46 assert 49
            advertised tools; t/15's doc-sync guard (+2) confirms pcg_smells is in INSTRUCTIONS and the skill.

0.060     2026-06-25
          - New: `pcg tidy` / pcg_tidy (48 MCP tools) -- a one-call CLEANUP DASHBOARD that composes the
            detectors into one curated, de-overlapped survey so an agent gets the whole cleanup surface in a
            single call, each item paired with the WRITE tool that fixes it. Three disjoint buckets:
            REMOVABLE (unreferenced, non-exported subs `pcg rm` deletes outright), RETRACTABLE (exported subs
            no other in-repo package uses -- stop exporting, then remove; kept separate because rm refuses
            exported subs), and CLONES (structural duplicate groups `pcg dedupe` collapses). A survey, not an
            apply: it names the exact follow-up commands but changes nothing. Same dead-code/clone caveats as
            its components (dynamic dispatch + downstream consumers are invisible). Opens the 8th wave.
            New Query::tidy (composes unused + dead_exports + duplication); Format::tidy; CLI `pcg tidy`;
            `--limit` / `--min-nodes` tune the clones bucket.
          - Tests +18 (1423 total): t/100 (+16: the three buckets are disjoint and correctly populated -- an
            orphan private sub is removable, a called clone is not, an exported dead sub is retractable not
            removable, a cross-package-called export is neither; the renderer names the rm/dedupe commands and
            the clean-state message). t/15 + t/46 assert 48 advertised tools; t/15's doc-sync guard (+2)
            confirms pcg_tidy is surfaced in both the MCP INSTRUCTIONS catalog and the deployed skill.

0.059     2026-06-23
          - New: `pcg scaffold <symbol>` / pcg_scaffold (47 MCP tools) -- generate a POD + test SKELETON
            (with TODO placeholders) for a sub, derived from its signature: a `=head2` POD stub (using
            $obj->name and dropping the invocant for a method) and a Test2::V0 test stub that loads the
            package and calls the sub with one placeholder argument per parameter, plus an assertion to fill
            in. The actionable starting point for pcg_untested / pcg_undocumented. Read-only -- it emits text
            to adapt, writes nothing. New Query::scaffold + _sig_params; Format::scaffold; CLI `pcg scaffold`.
            Closes the 7th wave (detection -> action): checkargs, doccheck, changelog, dedupe, rm, scaffold.
          - Tests +13 (1405 total): t/99 (a function scaffold with one placeholder per param, a method
            scaffold that drops the invocant and uses $obj->, a no-arg sub, an unknown-symbol error).

0.058     2026-06-23
          - New: `pcg rm <target>` / pcg_rm (46 MCP tools) -- the FIFTH write tool, the actionable
            follow-up to pcg_unused: safely DELETE a dead sub. Refuses if the target is still called by any
            in-repo node (lists the callers) or is exported (it may have out-of-repo consumers). When it IS
            dead, removes it AND cascade-removes the now-dead PRIVATE helpers it solely used (recursively,
            to a fixed point), so a whole dead subtree goes at once. Dry-run unless apply. New Refactor::rm
            + _apply_removals (reuses _find_sub + a byte-span remover); Format::rm; CLI `pcg rm`.
          - Tests +19 (1392 total): t/98 (a still-called sub refused with the caller listed; a dead sub + its
            sole-use private helper removed while a shared helper survives; the file still parses; dry-run
            writes nothing; an exported sub refused).

0.057     2026-06-23
          - New: `pcg dedupe <target>` / pcg_dedupe (45 MCP tools) -- the FOURTH write tool, the inverse of
            copy-paste: de-duplicate a structural clone group (from `pcg duplication`). Keep the target
            function as the canonical copy and rewrite every OTHER plain function in the group whose
            signature+body is BYTE-IDENTICAL into a one-line delegation `sub name { goto &Canonical }` --
            the duplicated logic lives in one place while every name stays callable. Conservative by design:
            only EXACT (type-1) duplicate FUNCTIONS are rewritten; type-2 clones (renamed vars / changed
            literals) and methods are reported, never edited. Dry-run unless apply. New Refactor::dedupe +
            _sub_rest (reuses _find_sub + _apply_inline); Format::dedupe; CLI `pcg dedupe`.
          - Tests +20 (1373 total): t/97 (an exact duplicate rewritten to delegate, a type-2 clone left
            untouched, the canonical preserved, the rewritten file still parses, dry-run writes nothing, a
            non-clone target errors, a cross-package clone whose file does not load the canonical skipped,
            and a clone group carrying an :attribute refused outright).

0.056     2026-06-23
          - New: `pcg changelog <ref>` / pcg_changelog (44 MCP tools) -- draft a release-notes / Changes
            entry from the STRUCTURAL diff vs a git ref: the added / removed / signature-changed
            functions/methods/constants/packages grouped under Added / Removed / Changed, each tagged
            public-vs-internal and breaking-vs-not, with the suggested version bump at the top. A
            ready-to-edit scaffold for a CPAN-style Changes entry (turn the bullets into prose before
            release) -- complements semver, which only recommends the bump. Reuses App::PerlGraph::Diff;
            new Format::changelog; CLI `pcg changelog`. Needs a git work tree.
          - Tests +13 (1353 total): t/96 (the major/minor/patch bump levels, the Added/Removed/Changed
            grouping, internal-vs-public and breaking tagging, the signature old->new line, the empty case).

0.055     2026-06-23
          - New: `pcg doccheck` / pcg_doccheck (43 MCP tools) -- a doc-DRIFT linter (distinct from
            undocumented, which is MISSING POD): call-shaped POD entries (`=head2 name($args)` /
            `=item C<< $obj->name >>`) documenting a method/function that no longer exists in the
            documenting file's package(s) or their @ISA -- a method removed or renamed while its docs were
            left behind. Package + MRO aware (an inherited method documented in a subclass is fine),
            auto-provided names (new/import/...) skipped, and the call form (parens or `->`) is required so
            prose section headings ('DESCRIPTION', 'Configuration') never match. New Query::doccheck +
            _pod_api_names; Format::doccheck; CLI `pcg doccheck`. 0 false positives dogfooding pcg.
          - Tests +15 (1340 total): t/95 (a removed method via =head2 and via =item, an inherited method,
            a real method, a documented `use constant`, a prose heading, and an auto-provided new() -- only
            the two stale entries flagged).

0.054     2026-06-23
          - New: `pcg checkargs` / pcg_checkargs (42 MCP tools) -- a static BUG FINDER, sibling to
            checkcalls: calls that pass the wrong NUMBER of arguments to an in-repo sub whose SIGNATURE
            fixes its arity (`sub f ($a, $b)` = exactly 2; a `$b = 5` default = 1-2; a slurpy @rest / %opt
            = variadic, not checked) -- too few or too many args, which Perl only catches at runtime.
            Re-parses each calling file to count the positional args at the call site: a `->method` call's
            implicit invocant is counted toward @_, and a splat arg (@list / a list-returning call) makes a
            site indeterminate and is skipped. Precise, not exhaustive: a same-package `$self->method` call
            is matched so a `$x->foo` is never checked against an unrelated `Other::foo`, a callee whose
            qualified name is defined twice (e.g. main:: in two scripts) is skipped as resolution-ambiguous,
            and a `my ($x) = @_` sub has no signature to check. New Query::checkargs + _sig_arity /
            _call_sites / _count_args; Format::checkargs; CLI `pcg checkargs`. 0 false positives dogfooding
            pcg itself. Opens a 7th wave -- turning the graph's detectors into actions + new finders.
          - Tests +14 (1325 total): t/94 (too-few / too-many function calls, a same-package method call's
            invocant, plus the negatives -- a defaulted param, a slurpy signature, and a splat arg, none flagged).

0.053     2026-06-23
          - New: `pcg suggest-reviewers <ref>` / pcg_suggest_reviewers (41 MCP tools) -- who should
            review a change: the authors of the files changed vs <ref>, ranked by how many commits
            they have made to that touched code (git authorship x the diff). The people who wrote
            the changed code review it best; the change's own author tends to rank first, so pick
            the next most familiar. New Query::suggest_reviewers; Format::suggest_reviewers; CLI `pcg
            suggest-reviewers` (reuses Git::authors + Git::changed). Needs a git work tree.
          - Tests +15 (1311 total): t/93 (ranking by commit total across the changed files, an
            author of an unchanged file excluded, the per-reviewer file list, the rendered report).
          - Completes the sixth feature wave (0.048-0.053): checkcalls, duplication, inline, metrics,
            dead-exports, suggest-reviewers. 41 MCP tools.

0.052     2026-06-23
          - New: `pcg dead-exports` / pcg_dead_exports (40 MCP tools) -- exported FUNCTIONS/METHODS
            (@EXPORT / @EXPORT_OK) that NO other in-repo package calls: public API you could stop
            exporting to shrink the surface. A caller in any OTHER package (tests included) makes an
            export live; same-package use does not. Constants are excluded (their bareword use is not
            call-tracked). Honest caveat: a CPAN module's exports may serve external / downstream
            consumers the graph can't see -- candidates to verify, not certain removals. New
            Query::dead_exports; Format::dead_exports; CLI `pcg dead-exports`.
          - Tests +10 (1296 total): t/92 (a dead export + a same-package-only export flagged, a
            cross-package-called export not flagged).

0.051     2026-06-23
          - New: `pcg metrics` / pcg_metrics (39 MCP tools) -- a one-call code-health snapshot for
            triage or a release gate: scale (files/packages/subs/public-API/nodes/edges), static
            resolution %, test + POD coverage of the public API, high-complexity sub count, dead
            code, structural clone groups, and dependency cycles, plus a flagged "concerns" summary.
            Composes the existing analyses (unused / untested / undocumented / duplication / cycles)
            into headline numbers; spans all indexed files (tests included). New Query::metrics;
            Format::metrics; CLI `pcg metrics`.
          - Tests +21 (1286 total): t/91 (the metric keys, percentages bounded to [0,100], and the
            rendered dashboard + concerns summary).

0.050     2026-06-23
          - New: `pcg inline` / pcg_inline (38 MCP tools) -- the THIRD write tool, the inverse of
            extracting a helper: inline a simple FUNCTION at its resolved call sites and remove the
            definition. Each call becomes a `do { my (params) = (args); body }` block -- binds the
            arguments once, preserves precedence, supports multi-statement bodies. Strictly scoped
            for safety: a plain function (not a method), params via a leading `my (...) = @_` or a
            simple all-scalar signature, and a body with no return / wantarray / shift / pop /
            $_[N] / caller / goto / local (control flow a do-block cannot preserve). Dynamic $obj->method +
            unresolved sites are reported and the definition kept; refuses (with a reason) anything
            unsafe. Dry-run by default. New Refactor::inline + _find_sub / _calls_by_pos /
            _inline_template / _apply_inline (byte-span replacement); Format::inline; CLI `pcg inline`.
          - Tests +29 (1265 total): t/90 (unpack-idiom + signature inline with args bound once, def
            removal, dry-run, the return refusal, a method-call site -> frontier + def kept, a
            recursive self-call -> frontier, an exported function -> def kept, a $1-shaped argument
            inlined literally, and multi-package same-name targeting -- the file re-parses each time).

0.049     2026-06-23
          - New: `pcg duplication` / pcg_duplication (37 MCP tools) -- structural clone detection:
            groups subs whose BODY has an identical CST shape (a per-sub `dup` fingerprint -- the
            node-type sequence with identifiers and literals abstracted away), so type-1 (exact) and
            type-2 (copy-paste with renamed vars / changed constants) duplicates are caught. Ranked
            by size x copies, so the biggest, most-copied groups -- the best extract-a-shared-helper /
            DRY targets -- lead. Type-3 near-dupes are NOT grouped, so a group is a real structural
            match. New Extractor::_body_fingerprint (stored as metadata.dup; EXTRACTION_VERSION 7->8);
            Query::duplication; Format::duplication; CLI `pcg duplication` (--limit / --min-nodes).
          - Tests +13 (1236 total): t/89 (a type-2 pair groups, a structurally-different sub does not,
            the min-nodes floor). Dogfooding flagged real clones in pcg (the mirrored _cmd_* CLI
            handlers + copy-pasted test helpers).

0.048     2026-06-23
          - New: `pcg checkcalls` / pcg_checkcalls (36 MCP tools) -- a static BUG FINDER turning the
            resolved graph into a linter: `$obj->method` sites where the receiver class is KNOWN (a
            $self/$class invocant, an inferred `my $x = Class->new`, or a bareword Class->method) and
            that class + its FULL in-repo MRO defines no such method -- typos and calls into renamed/
            removed API that Perl misses until runtime. Conservative gate (closed in-repo MRO, no
            AUTOLOAD, not a universal/lifecycle method; `has`/`field`/`is=>rwp` accessors understood)
            keeps false positives near zero; honest about the residue (runtime-injected methods,
            `handles` delegation) that `pcg index --runtime` resolves. New Query::checkcalls +
            Resolver::receiver_class/mro; Format::checkcalls; CLI `pcg checkcalls`.
          - Fix (surfaced by dogfooding checkcalls -- 0 false positives on pcg only after these; both
            also improve resolution generally): (1) `$self->{slot} = Class->new` no longer mis-types
            `$self` itself (it typed the base var, mis-resolving every later `$self->method`); (2) Moo
            `is => rwp` now emits the generated private writer `_set_<attr>` as a node. EXTRACTION_VERSION 6->7.
          - Tests +17 (1223 total): t/88 (the genuine bug + every false-positive guard incl. the rwp writer).

0.047     2026-06-22
          - Docs / discoverability polish so an agent reaches for the right tool naturally:
            restructured the MCP INSTRUCTIONS catalog from one dense run-on into intent-grouped
            routing lines (ORIENT / UNDERSTAND / ARCHITECTURE / HISTORY / QUALITY & RELEASE /
            REFACTOR / LIFECYCLE / UNRESOLVED FRONTIER), leading with the provenance trust model;
            pcg_overview is now advertised FIRST (the recommended first call); added pcg_node to
            the deployed skill; brought the App::PerlGraph SYNOPSIS up to date (context, layers,
            prereqs, undocumented, owners, semver, move, export html).
          - New doc-sync GUARD (t/15): every advertised tool must be named in BOTH the INSTRUCTIONS
            catalog and the skill -- locks the recurring drift where a shipped tool never reaches
            the agent-facing docs. No new tool, no behavior change (still 35 tools).
          - Tests +71 (1206 total): t/15 (the per-tool catalog/skill coverage guard + overview-first).

0.046     2026-06-22
          - New: `pcg owners` / pcg_owners (35 MCP tools) -- code ownership x importance for
            bus-factor: each indexed file's primary author (most commits, from git) and that
            author's share, ranked by how depended-upon the file is (cross-file inbound call /
            reference edges). A high-importance file owned almost entirely by one author is
            flagged a bus-factor risk -- where knowledge is concentrated in code many things
            depend on. New Git::authors; Query::owners; Format::owners; CLI `pcg owners`.
          - Tests +10 (1135 total): t/87 (cross-file fan-in incl. same-file edges excluded,
            primary-owner + share, ranking, and the bus-factor-risk flag on / off).

0.045     2026-06-22
          - New: `pcg export --format html` -- a SELF-CONTAINED interactive graph (no external / CDN
            dependency): nodes/edges are embedded as JSON and laid out by a small inline force-
            directed simulation rendered to SVG. Hover a node to highlight its neighbours, drag to
            reposition, search to locate; nodes colored by kind and sized by degree. For onboarding
            / docs / review of a (sub)graph -- pair with --around SYM --depth N. New
            Format::_export_html (the data is injected by literal substr, never an interpolating
            s///, so arbitrary symbol names are safe).
          - Tests +6 (1125 total): t/37 (valid document, data injected, placeholder replaced, the
            inline renderer, no external script src, and the empty-graph case).

0.044     2026-06-22
          - New: `pcg move <Old::sub> <NewPkg>` / pcg_move (34 MCP tools) -- the SECOND write tool:
            move a function to another (already-existing) package using the graph. It relocates the
            sub's source from its origin file into the target package's file and requalifies every
            resolved call site (Foo::bar and bareword bar -> NewPkg::bar). Dynamic $obj->method
            dispatch + stale `use` imports are reported for manual review, never silently edited.
            Dry-run by default. New Refactor::move + _relocate / _pkg_line (reuses rename's
            resolver-confirmed call-site machinery); Format::move; CLI `pcg move`.
          - Tests +14 (1119 total): t/86 (relocate + requalify across files, both edited files still
            parse, the dry-run, and the unknown-symbol / unknown-target / same-package / collision errors).

0.043     2026-06-22
          - Taint-aware sinks: `pcg sinks` / pcg_sinks now flags each command/SQL sink as [dynamic]
            when its STRING argument is built from a variable -- interpolated (do("...$id") /
            system("rm $f")), concatenated, or a bare variable -- the injection-SHAPED sites --
            vs parameterized/constant (do("...?", $id) / system("ls","-l")) which are safe. The
            route-reachable [dynamic] sinks are the real attack surface. A big precision gain over
            the pure name-heuristic (the difference between a vuln and safe code), computed at
            extraction from the call argument AST. Still honest -- no full source->sink dataflow,
            so a [dynamic] reached sink is a site to VERIFY, not a confirmed bug. New Extractor::
            _sink_dynamic / _has_interp_var; sink metadata gains `dynamic`; Query / Format::sinks
            carry and render it. EXTRACTION_VERSION 5->6 (a sync after upgrade re-extracts).
          - Tests +3 (1105 total): t/78 (interpolated string -> dynamic; placeholdered DBI +
            list-form system() -> safe).

0.042     2026-06-22
          - New: `pcg layers` / pcg_layers (33 MCP tools) -- architecture stratification: groups the
            project's modules into LAYERS by their longest dependency-path depth (layer 0 imports /
            inherits nothing internal; each higher layer builds only on lower ones), and flags
            cyclic dependencies as layering violations. Reveals the architectural shape at a glance
            -- on this codebase: Model / Schema / Parser (layer 0) -> Store / Resolver (1) -> Query /
            Indexer (2) -> ... -> MCP -> Installer -> CLI (top). A clean architecture is a DAG. New
            Query::layers (memoized longest-path DFS with back-edge detection); Format::layers; CLI
            `pcg layers`.
          - Tests +8 (1102 total): t/85 (a 3-layer chain stratifies correctly + a 2-module cycle is
            reported as a layering violation).

0.041     2026-06-22
          - New: `pcg undocumented [module]` / pcg_undocumented (32 MCP tools) -- public API
            symbols (function/method/constant) carrying no POD docstring: the same public surface
            as `untested` / `api`, filtered to those a reader gets no documentation for. A
            documentation-coverage check for a release; completes the CPAN-hygiene trio
            (semver / prereqs / undocumented). New Query::undocumented; Format::undocumented; CLI
            `pcg undocumented`.
          - Tests +8 (1094 total): t/84 (documented excluded, whitespace-only docstring counts as
