0.032     2026-06-22
          - New: security attack-surface analysis -- `pcg sinks` / pcg_sinks. At extraction
            time it marks command-execution (system/exec/syscall) and SQL-execution (DBI
            do/execute/select*) call sites as `sink` edges, then for a web app computes which
            routes/endpoints can transitively REACH each sink (route handler -> forward call
            closure). On a Mojo::Lite/Dancer2 app it reports e.g. "GET /run -> command system
            in main::do_thing" -- the endpoints where a tainted request value could reach a
            dangerous call. Heuristic by call name (a placeholdered DBI call is safe), so a
            reached sink is a site to VERIFY, not a confirmed bug; sink sites with no reaching
            route are still listed. New Model::sink_type + the `sink` edge kind; Query::sinks;
            CLI `pcg sinks`; pcg_sinks (27 MCP tools). EXTRACTION_VERSION 2->3 (a sync after
            upgrade re-extracts to add the sink edges).
          - Tests +12 (1018 total): t/78 (command + sql sink typing, route->sink reachability,
            a sink-free route excluded, the non-web no-route case, the rendered report).

0.031     2026-06-22
          - New: graph-driven rename codemod -- `pcg rename Old::sub new` / pcg_rename. Renames
            a function/method within its package by using the resolved graph to find every
            reference precisely and the RESOLVER to decide which call sites actually target
            it: the definition, qualified calls (Foo::bar), bareword calls (bar()), and
            $self->method dispatch the heuristic tied to the symbol are all renamed -- while a
            same-named method on a DIFFERENT class, and dynamic $obj->method dispatch the
            resolver cannot tie to this symbol, are left alone and REPORTED for manual review
            (a rename that knows what it cannot see). Each affected file is re-parsed for
            byte-precise positions and every edit is re-validated against the current bytes
            before writing (a stale index skips a site rather than corrupting it). Dry-run by
            default; --apply / apply:true writes, then call pcg sync. New App::PerlGraph::
            Refactor; CLI `pcg rename`; pcg_rename -- the first WRITE tool (26 MCP tools).
          - Tests +20 (1006 total): t/77 (def/qualified/bareword/resolved-method renamed,
            other-class + dynamic-dispatch sites untouched, dry-run vs --apply, the renamed
            file still parses, the error/collision paths).

