0.026     2026-06-21
          - Pre-release review (multi-agent: correctness / consistency / cleanliness /
            security / performance; findings adversarially verified). Fixes:
            * SECURITY (git argument injection -> arbitrary file write): a ref/`--since`
              value beginning with `-` was passed bare to git, so e.g.
              `pcg review --output=FILE` (or the pcg_review/pcg_diff/pcg_affected MCP
              tools, which an agent may drive on untrusted input) ran
              `git diff ... --output=FILE`, writing an arbitrary file. Git refs can
              never start with `-`, so Git::changed/show/churn now reject such values
              at the chokepoint (Git::_safe_ref).
            * Format::resolved no longer garbles the receiver-type pcg_resolve form
              ({caller,receiver,class}): it carries no method/target keys, which produced
              uninitialized-value warnings and a blank "->" line. Now rendered as
              "`caller` `receiver` is `Class` -- N call(s) resolved".
            * pcg_diff via MCP no longer requires an index (it parses git directly, like
              the CLI `pcg diff`); pcg_review still needs one.
            * Git::_run no longer permanently silences STDERR when the save-dup fails -- it
              only redirects to /dev/null when it can later restore (matters for the
              long-lived MCP/LSP servers).
            * `pcg risk --since REF` (+ pcg_risk since) weights risk by churn on the current
              branch -- wiring Git::churn's `since`, previously dead. MCP reached CLI parity:
              pcg_cochange gained max_files, pcg_affected gained `since` (CI triage -- tests
              to run for the diff vs main -- in one MCP call).
            * _index_parallel reaps already-forked workers if a later fork fails (no zombies
              in the long-lived server). Query::resolve persists each learned method once,
              not once per call site. Format::unresolved points at the preferred form.
            * CLI `pcg affected --since` now uses git `--relative` (like diff/review/risk),
              fixing it for a project nested in a larger repo, and shares Git::changed --
              removing a duplicate git wrapper (`_git_changed`) that also skipped the
              Perl-file filter.
            * Runtime optree enricher (`pcg index --runtime`): _find_gv resolved named
              function calls only on a NON-threaded perl (gv = B::SVOP); on a THREADED
              perl -- the default Debian/Ubuntu/Fedora/macOS build -- gv ops are B::PADOP
              (the GV lives in the pad, not the op), so every optree function-call edge
              was silently dropped. Now reads the GV from the CV's pad via op->padix; a
              threaded CI matrix entry now exercises that path.
          - Cleanliness: Resolver SUPER computes the enclosing package once; _resolve_call
            uses a single callable closure (was three copies of the same grep); Extractor
            _attr_value and Runtime _cv_owner de-dup repeated idioms; Format::_breaking_count.
            Fixed a stranded doc-comment that mislabeled Query::hotspots, and strengthened
            t/00's vacuous version assertion.
          - Performance (large-graph N+1s): resolve_all memoizes the enclosing-package
            lookup per node (was one node() query per unresolved ref -- 30k on jakutia);
            pcg_unresolved batches its caller-name and candidate-method lookups into two
            queries (was O(refs)+O(methods)) via new Store node_qnames/callables_by_name.
          - Packaging: cpanfile now `recommends` Linux::Inotify2 (parity with Makefile.PL,
            so `cpanm --installdeps` surfaces the event-driven `pcg watch` option).
          - Docs synced: README (pcg_index deps, risk --since, full provenance list, grammar),
