            clears ~110 UNIVERSAL non-gaps.
          - Analysis note: the remaining unresolved is overwhelmingly opaque dispatch
            into CPAN classes and dynamic/runtime mechanisms -- the static ceiling for
            a framework app; `pcg index --runtime` (and a future cross-distribution
            `--deps` pass) are the real levers there.
          - t/72 covers SUPER resolution, UNIVERSAL consumption, and that a genuine
            opaque call is not over-consumed.

0.022     2026-06-21
          - New `pcg review <ref>` command + `pcg_review` MCP tool (24 tools), and
            App::PerlGraph::Review. One call composes the change analyses into a
            branch/PR review: the structural diff vs the ref (added/removed/
            re-signatured symbols, breaking PUBLIC API flagged), the blast radius
            (files affected), the tests to run, and each touched symbol's caller
            count. The agent-native "review this branch" operation -- diff +
            affected + impact in one report.
          - t/71 covers the composition (breaking detection, affected tests, format).

0.021     2026-06-20
          - New `pcg diff <ref>` command + `pcg_diff` MCP tool (23 tools), and a new
            App::PerlGraph::Diff module. Structural ("semantic") diff vs a git ref:
            which functions/methods/constants/packages were added, removed, or had
            their signature change between the ref and the working tree -- with
            breaking changes (removed or re-signatured PUBLIC API) flagged. Both
            sides are parsed fresh (the ref via `git show`), so it is independent
            of how stale the on-disk graph is. Ideal for reviewing a branch/PR.
            Git module gained changed/show/prefix (subdir-aware) and now silences
            git's own diagnostics. t/70 covers add/remove/signature-change, the
            breaking flag, private exclusion, and the format.

0.020     2026-06-20
          - New `pcg cochange` command + `pcg_cochange` MCP tool (22 tools): logical
            (temporal) coupling -- code files that change together in git history,
            ranked by Jaccard of their commit sets. Each pair is flagged [no static
            link] when the call graph has no edge between them, so the high-coupling
            unlinked pairs are HIDDEN dependencies static analysis can't see.
            --min-support / --max-files (skip sweeping commits like version bumps).
          - App::PerlGraph::Git now passes --relative so churn/co-change paths are
            relative to the indexed root (matching the graph) even when the project
            is a subdir of a larger git repo -- this also fixes `pcg risk` there.
            New Store::files_statically_linked.
          - t/69 covers the mining, the hidden-vs-linked flag, support filtering,
            non-code exclusion, and the format.

0.019     2026-06-20
          - New `pcg risk` command + `pcg_risk` MCP tool (21 tools), and a new
            App::PerlGraph::Git module (read-only `git log` wrapper). History-aware
            risk: symbols ranked by churn (commits touching their file) x fan-in
            (how many depend on them) -- the frequently-changed AND widely-depended-
            upon code that is the top refactor/test target (the CodeScene-style
            heuristic, over pcg's resolved call graph). Each row shows churn,
            callers, complexity and the score; on the pcg repo it surfaces
            Store::init (churned 18x, 55 callers). Degrades cleanly outside a git
            work tree. Query::risk takes the churn map, staying git-agnostic.
          - t/68 covers the Git module (churn/transactions/availability) and
            Query::risk + Format::risk.

0.018     2026-06-20
          - Interprocedural return-type inference: a `Class->new` builder sub
            (`sub make_db { Store->new }` / `return Store->new`) records its return
            type, so `make_db()->save` and `$self->make_db->save` resolve against
            Store's MRO (`inferred`). Composes with the local + attribute type
            inference; same precision (only a literal-class constructor, only when
            the method exists there). New Extractor _constructor_class/_return_class;
            the resolver chain handler gained a base_func (func()->m) case.
          - t/67 covers the capture (implicit + explicit returns, the ambiguous/
            non-constructor negatives) and both chain forms.

0.017     2026-06-20
          - Cyclomatic complexity per sub: the extractor counts decision points
            (if/elsif/unless/while/until/for/foreach/when, ternary, &&/||////and/or)
            in each sub's CST and stores metadata.complexity (omitted when trivially
            1). Surfaced three ways: in `pcg node`/`explore` headers, as a `cx N`
            annotation on hotspots fan-in rows (complex AND widely-used = top risk),
            and a new "Most complex (cyclomatic)" hotspots section (Store::top_complex).
            On torus it flags main::_run_physics_worker at cx 78. (Picked up on the
            next full reindex / file change.)
          - t/66 covers the metric + node-view/hotspots rendering; t/61 the ranking.

0.016     2026-06-20
          - New `pcg untested` command + `pcg_untested` MCP tool (20 tools): the
            public API surface (exported / non-_ functions, methods, constants)
            that no test file statically reaches. One cheap forward closure from
            the test files, then api() minus what was reached. Omit the module for
            the whole project. (A symbol exercised only via opaque $obj->method
            dispatch from a test is invisible to static analysis and may appear.)
          - New Store::node_file_paths (distinct file_paths from nodes, works on
            in-memory graphs). t/65 covers the gap detection, private exclusion,
            format, and module scoping.

0.015     2026-06-20
          - Added a portable end-to-end LSP test (t/64): indexes a project with the
            real CLI, then drives the actual `pcg lsp` binary over Content-Length-
            framed stdio the way an editor does (initialize, the initialized +
            didOpen notifications, a position-based textDocument/definition, exit)
            and asserts go-to-def resolves across files to the right line. Hardens
            the editor-readiness claim short of a GUI client.

0.014     2026-06-20
          - `pcg hotspots` deepened: each fan-in row now shows its transitive
            blast radius (reverse-reachable callers, for the shown rows), so a
            low-fan-in / high-reach symbol stops hiding -- on torus,
            Torus::Math::torus_dist has 7 direct callers but 20 transitive. Plus a
            new "most coupled modules" section (efferent coupling: packages that
            depend on the most other modules, reusing deps()).
          - t/61 covers the blast-radius annotation and the coupling ranking (+5).

0.013     2026-06-20
          - LSP: `workspace/symbol` (the editor's project-wide "go to symbol") --
            a case-insensitive substring match over every symbol in the graph,
            backed by a new Store::symbols_like (LIKE on name/qualified_name,
            shortest-first). Advertised via `workspaceSymbolProvider`.
          - LSP hardened for real clients: the notification stream an editor
            sends (textDocument/didOpen / didChange / didClose, $/setTrace, ...) is
            silently ignored, never answered. t/63 covers both additions (+6).

0.012     2026-06-20
          - New `pcg lsp`: a minimal Language Server over the graph (stdio, LSP
            base protocol). go-to-definition, find-references, hover and document
            symbols, answered from the RESOLVED call graph -- so go-to-def follows
            the `$obj->method` dispatch the resolver (and `--runtime`) tied down,
            which a tags/parser-based Perl LSP can't. Read-only and stateless; keep
            the graph fresh with `pcg watch`. New App::PerlGraph::LSP plus Store
            position lookups (edges_at_source / node_at_start / node_covering) and
            Query navigation (definition_at / references_at / symbol_at).
          - t/62 covers the position queries; t/63 the LSP protocol -- initialize
            capabilities, the four navigation methods, shutdown/unknown/notification
            edges, and the Content-Length framing both directions. Protocol-level
            validated; editor-client testing still pending.

0.011     2026-06-20
          - New `pcg hotspots` command + `pcg_hotspots` MCP tool (19 tools total):
            call-graph centrality for review/refactor triage -- the most
            depended-upon symbols (highest fan-in -> high blast radius) and the
            most complex (highest fan-out), each with its degree and location.
            `--limit N` (default 15). Cheap SQL aggregates over the existing
            calls/references edges; codebase-independent (unlike the type-inference
            work, every graph has a call structure to rank).
          - t/61 covers the ranking, callable-only filter, format, and CLI/MCP glue.

0.010     2026-06-20
          - Attribute-type inference (chained dispatch): an accessor with a
            declared class type -- Moo/Moose `has x => (isa => 'Class')` or native
            `field $x :reader :isa(Class)` -- gives `$self->x` a return type, so
            the chained `$self->x->method` resolves against Class's MRO
            (`inferred`). Composes with the 0.009 local inference, e.g.
            `my $o = App->new; $o->x->method`. High precision: only a literal-class
            type, only when the method exists there, never a fabricated edge.
            (Helps typed-OO codebases; plain-OO / untyped-Mojo apps declare no
            such types, so no effect there.)
          - Resolver MRO walk factored into `_method_in`. t/60 covers Moo isa,
            native field :isa, the untyped/non-class negatives, and the compose.

0.009     2026-06-20
          - Local (intraprocedural) type inference: `my $x = Class->new; ...;
            $x->method` now resolves `$x->method` against Class's MRO
            deterministically -- new `inferred` provenance, ranked above
            `heuristic` and below `static` (runtime optree/MOP still upgrades it).
            High precision: only the literal-class `->new` idiom, scoped per sub,
            and never an edge to a method the class lacks. Closes a chunk of opaque
            `$obj->method` dispatch with no --runtime and no LLM (+20 call edges,
            ~10% of the call graph, on a plain-OO codebase; correctly 0 where the
            local constructors are all CPAN classes).
          - Docs/skill note the new provenance; t/59 covers the happy path,
            per-sub scoping, ambiguity-without-false-positives, and non-fabrication.

0.008     2026-06-19
          - Review-pass fixes: `has` accessor extraction no longer mines
            option-looking keys (accessor/reader/writer/is) out of a default
            sub or hashref/arrayref value (could emit a wrongly-named accessor);
            `pcg watch` rejects an unknown --flag instead of treating it as the
            root (which could silently enter the watch loop); `Query::resolve`
            fetches the unresolved set once, not once per resolution in a batch.
          - pcg_unresolved honors limit:0; the MCP status hint points at
            pcg_index runtime:true / pcg_resolve; PROVENANCE includes `llm`;
            README tool list/count corrected (18). New `Store::ref_anchor` helper
            de-duplicates the (caller, method, receiver) extraction.
          - Test coverage added: CLI deps/cycles/api/covers/unresolved glue,
            resolve missing-field + name/limit filters, has writer, watch --json
            added/deleted events, project-defined qualified-external resolution.

0.007     2026-06-19
          - Known-external call recognition: bareword/qualified calls to common
            CPAN exports (Test::More/Test2/Test::Fatal, Carp, List::Util,
            Scalar::Util, JSON) and qualified externals (AE::/EV::/POSIX::/...)
            that don't resolve to a project symbol are now recognized as external
            instead of inflating the "unresolved" count. A bare name the project
            itself defines is never mistaken for a CPAN export. On real codebases
            this cut bareword-unresolved ~95% (torus 389->19, Feersum 3736->187),
            so `pcg status`'s remaining unresolved is the real method-dispatch
            frontier, not test/CPAN noise.
          - `pcg install` now deploys a `perl-codegraph` Claude Code skill to
            ~/.claude/skills/ (removed by `pcg uninstall`), so an agent
            automatically prefers the graph -- and uses it wisely -- when working
            on a Perl codebase. The MCP server's own instructions remain the
            always-loaded usage doc.

0.006     2026-06-19
          - Fixed a path-keying bug: file paths were keyed by the root *spelling*,
            so indexing a project as `.` and as its absolute path produced
            different keys -- a sync under the other spelling saw every file as
            deleted+new (a spurious full reindex). Paths are now stored canonically
            (relative to the root); the on-disk path is reconstructed where needed.
            This matters when a `pcg watch /abs/path` and `pcg serve --mcp` (root
            `.`) run on the same project.
          - `pcg watch --json`: emit one structured event per change --
            { added, changed, deleted, affected_tests } -- so an agent can monitor
            the stream and react (e.g. re-run the affected tests). Plain `pcg watch`
            now also reports deletions (it previously printed only on reindex>0).
          - sync() returns the add/change/delete file lists, not just counts.

0.005     2026-06-19
          - Agent-mediated resolution of opaque method dispatch. `pcg_unresolved`
            (MCP) / `pcg unresolved` (CLI) surfaces the `$obj->method` calls that
            static analysis can't tie to a class but which DO match real candidate
            methods in the graph, each with its candidates and call frequency.
            The agent infers each receiver's class and calls `pcg_resolve` to
            record it: a call edge with `llm` provenance (lowest rank, so any
            later static/runtime resolution overrides it), validated against real
            nodes (hallucinated targets rejected). Resolutions persist in a new
            `resolutions` table and are re-applied after every reindex.
          - Only variable receivers ($x, $self->{x}) are surfaced -- a literal
            `Class->method` that didn't resolve is external, not inferrable.

0.004     2026-06-19
          - Mojolicious support (found by auditing real Mojo codebases):
            * Mojo::Base `has` attributes now emit accessor methods (all forms:
              `has 'x'`, `has [qw(a b)]`, `has x => default/sub`), so `$self->x`
              resolves -- including inherited accessors up the MRO.
            * `helper name => sub` / `$app->helper(name => sub)` registrations
              become method nodes; a matching `$c->name` call resolves to the
              helper (framework provenance).
          - Completed the builtin list (pack/unpack/glob/fork/waitpid/unlink/
            system/exec/stat/socket/... and more), so core functions no longer
            masquerade as unresolved calls. The builtin filter now applies only
            to bareword calls -- `$obj->print` stays a method, not the builtin.
          - Indexer skips more noise: `.vscode` / `.idea`, and any nested git
            repo or `git worktree` (a non-root subdir with its own .git) -- these
            duplicated or bloated the graph (8x fewer files on one real tree).
          - `pcg status` / pcg_status break unresolved down into dynamic
            method-dispatch vs bareword calls, so the number is interpretable.

0.003     2026-06-19
          - Imported-symbol resolution: a bareword call to a symbol brought in by
            `use Some::Module qw(name)` now resolves to Some::Module::name even
            when the name is globally ambiguous (a local definition still wins).
          - Attribute accessors are resolved statically (no --runtime needed):
            Moo/Moose `has 'x' => (is => ...)` and native/Object::Pad
            `field $x :reader` emit accessor *method* nodes, so `$self->x`
            resolves. Honors reader/writer/accessor renames and `is => 'bare'`
            (no false accessors). A runtime MOP `field` now coexists with its
            static accessor method.
          - New queries / tools: `pcg deps` (module dependency graph),
            `pcg cycles` (circular dependencies), `pcg api` (a module's
            public/exported surface), `pcg covers` (which tests exercise a
            symbol). Exposed over MCP as pcg_deps / pcg_cycles / pcg_api /
            pcg_covers (sixteen tools total; re-run `pcg install`).
          - `pcg affected --since REF` takes its changed-file list from
            `git diff --name-only REF` (CI triage in one command).

0.002     2026-06-19
          - MCP lifecycle tools: pcg_index (with runtime option), pcg_sync and
            pcg_status. The server now bootstraps and refreshes its own graph
            in-session -- no separate `pcg index` run or restart needed. (Twelve
            MCP tools total; re-run `pcg install` to allow-list the new ones.)
          - `pcg --version`.
          - `pcg status` is now a setup/health check: it reports whether the
            parser works (grammar built, libtree-sitter recent enough) before the
            graph counts, so a broken setup is diagnosable.
          - A query before indexing now prints "No index -- run `pcg index`"
            instead of an empty result, and no longer creates a stray .pcg/.

0.001     2026-06-17
          - Initial release.
          - Static knowledge graph of a Perl codebase: packages, classes, subs,
            methods, fields, constants (`use constant`), calls, references,
            imports and inheritance, via tree-sitter-perl (Text::Treesitter) into
            a SQLite graph with FTS5.
          - Native OO (perl 5.38 `feature 'class'` and Object::Pad): `class`,
            `method` and `field` declarations, with `:isa`/`:does` inheritance.
          - Queries: search, node, explore, callers, callees, impact, path,
            affected, unused, status; plus index / sync / watch.
          - Static OO resolution (heuristic provenance): $self/$class method
            calls against the enclosing package, the transitive MRO -- inheritance
            via @ISA / parent / base / Moo·Moose `extends` / `Mojo::Base` / native
            `class :isa`, plus composed `with` / `:does` roles.
          - Incremental sync re-resolves dependents, so renames/removals leave
            no stale cross-file edges.
          - Parallel indexing: `pcg index --jobs N` (auto-detects cores) forks
            parse workers over the per-file parse phase, inserting serially in
            the parent -- byte-identical graph, much faster on large trees.
          - `pcg index --max-file-size SZ` (e.g. 1M) skips oversized files,
            which in a dependency tree are almost always generated data tables
            (Module::CoreList: 18 subs, 25k data lines) that dominate the index
            for almost no code graph -- ~10x on trees that contain one.
          - Opt-in runtime enrichment (--runtime): Devel::Symdump symbol table,
            B:: optree dynamic dispatch, and Moo/Moose MOP roles & attributes,
            run in a forked, timeout-guarded child.
          - Framework route resolvers (Dancer2 / Mojolicious::Lite / Catalyst)
            and an XS/C bridge linking Perl subs to their XSUBs.
          - Graph export to dot / mermaid / json (whole graph or a subgraph).
          - MCP server (newline-delimited JSON-RPC 2.0 over stdio) exposing
            nine tools, plus Claude Code install/uninstall.
